  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "Hi,\r\n\r\nWe are experiencing a memory leak in our operator and it seems to be caused by some Timers:\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/976373/66737404-27049080-ee6c-11e9-998e-91f75a5dd730.png)\r\n_See here the original issue: https://github.com/elastic/cloud-on-k8s/issues/1984_\r\n\r\nAfter some investigations I found out that the [waitingLoop](https://github.com/kubernetes/client-go/blob/172b42569ccacc5c33a885060fc0b7eab863d81e/util/workqueue/delaying_queue.go#L175)  can create a lot of timers (at least [1 every 10 seconds](https://github.com/kubernetes/client-go/blob/172b42569ccacc5c33a885060fc0b7eab863d81e/util/workqueue/delaying_queue.go#L172)) if the queue is not empty : \r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/client-go/blob/172b42569ccacc5c33a885060fc0b7eab863d81e/util/workqueue/delaying_queue.go#L207-L210\r\n\r\nThe problem here is that if the event in the queue is to expire in a \"far\" future the previous `nextReadyAt` timers will pile up and the memory will be reclaimed too late.\r\n\r\nCould someone confirm this scenario ?\r\n\r\nA fix would be to create some `Timer` with `time.NewTimer(...)` and close them when they are not needed (e.g. `ShutDown()` is called) or superseded by a most recent one.\r\n\r\nHappy to discuss the issue and contribute if needed.\r\n",
